Section section_02 (Chars 8751–12246):
Section Summary: Sir Joshua Reynolds quickly gained success as a portrait painter due to the quality of his work and the patronage he received. As his career progressed, he moved to larger studios, raised his prices, and became a prominent figure in society. Reynolds was not only a talented artist, but also a man of the world who enjoyed the company of intellectuals and artists, including Dr. Johnson, Garrick, and Burke. Despite his accomplishments, he had his flaws, including a touch of snobbery, jealousy, and vulgarity, which were somewhat refined through his associations with distinguished people. Overall, Reynolds was a complex figure, and it is more interesting to see him as a multifaceted person rather than trying to portray him as a moral exemplar.
